'''Kami-no-Mii Shrine''' (上御井神社) is a subordinate shrine of {{ill|Toyouke Daijingu|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|12=draft|12=draft}} (Geku) within the {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is located within Geku’s precincts, specifically beyond the {{ill|Otsu Shrine (Ise)|ja|大津神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, but it is in a restricted area, preventing general visitors from entering. Therefore, worshippers must perform rituals from a designated prayer spot nearby.<ref name="ic">Ise Bunka-sha (2008): p. 37</ref>

[[File:Kaminomiinojinja.jpg|thumb|Kami-no-Mii Shrine<br />The roof of the enclosure can be seen from the entrance of Yamada Construction Area, though general access is prohibited.]]

== Overview ==
Kami-no-Mii Shrine is located in {{ill|Toyo River Town|ja|豊川町 (伊勢市)|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ise, Mie|ja|伊勢市|12=draft|12=draft}}, within the precincts of Geku, specifically at the base of Mount Fujioka, one of the peaks forming {{ill|Takakura-yama (Ise)|ja|高倉山|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="uy">Ujiyamada City Hall (1929): p. 17</ref> Among the four subordinate shrines under Geku, Kami-no-Mii Ranks third.<ref>Ujiyamada City Hall (1929): pp. 15, 17</ref> There is no honden (main shrine); instead, the sacred well, Kami-no-Mii, is covered by an enclosure called the "Well Enclosure" (御井覆屋), surrounded by double layers of {{ill|Tamagaki|ja|玉垣|Tamagaki=Tamagaki|lt=wooden fences|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="jk3">Hozumi (2013): p. 163</ref>

The enshrined deity is the guardian deity of Kami-no-Mii (上御井鎮守神),<ref name="ic"/> worshipped as the protector of the sacred water used in Geku’s rituals<ref name="ic"/> or the well itself.<ref name="gk">Gakken Publishing (2013): p. 58</ref> During Geku’s ceremonies, Kami-no-Mii Shrine also receives offerings.<ref name="ij2">Sakurai (1998): p. 48</ref>

== Kami-no-Mii ==
Kami-no-Mii is a sacred well from which water is drawn for offering to the {{ill|kami|ja|神|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="gk"/> The nearby {{ill|Shimo-no-Mii Shrine|ja|下御井神社|12=draft|12=draft}} serves as a backup well for Kami-no-Mii.<ref name="ic"/><ref name="gk"/> Kami-no-Mii is said to have never dried up.<ref name="itv">[http://www.yoitokose.jp/ise/encyclopedia/s0003.php Shimo-no-Mii Shrine] - Ise Jingu Encyclopedia (retrieved September 11, 2013).</ref> However, the "Records of Omiya Affairs" (太神宮諸雑事記) notes that in 1050 (Eisho 5), Kami-no-Mii did dry up, prompting the use of water from Shimo-no-Mii.<ref name="jk3"/> During such events, envoys were dispatched to the imperial court to pray, reflecting the well's sanctity.<ref name="itv"/>

Every morning, priests draw water from Kami-no-Mii using long ladles while dressed in purified robes.<ref name="ij2"/><ref>Gakken Publishing (2013): p. 58</ref> Tradition dictates that priests must not see their reflection in the water.<ref name="ij3">Sakurai (1998): p. 49</ref> Additionally, the water used for brewing sacred sake at Ise Jingu is also drawn from this well.<ref>Kato (1979): p. 284</ref>

== History ==
The origin of Kami-no-Mii Shrine is unknown. Although the shrine is not listed in the "Toyuke-no-Miya Ritual Record," terms like "Well" (御井) and "Well deity" (御井神) are mentioned.<ref name="jk2">Hozumi (2013): p. 162</ref> The waka (Japanese poem) in the "Collection of Elegant Japanese Poems" (風雅和歌集) references Kami-no-Mii as follows:<ref name="ij1"/>

{{Cquote|Through the ages, endlessly drawn, this water will not run dry—Oshio-i, bestowed from the heavens.}}

The poem refers to the legend of Oshio-i (忍穂井), brought down from {{ill|Takamagahara|ja|高天原|12=draft|12=draft}} to {{ill|Hyuga Province|ja|日向国|12=draft|12=draft}}, then to the heavenly spring of {{ill|Tamba Province|ja|丹波国|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was finally moved to Ise with the enshrinement of {{ill|Toyouke Omikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="ij1"/>

During the Edo period, rituals involving Kami-no-Mii were overseen by the priestly Watarai family. The well was protected under state supervision until 1872, when control shifted to the Meiji government, but it was reinstated under the shrine’s jurisdiction the following year.<ref>Sakurai (1991): pp. 266, 272</ref>

== Access ==
Since general access to Kami-no-Mii Shrine is prohibited, visitors may worship from a nearby spot beyond {{ill|Otsu Shrine (Ise)|ja|大津神社|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="ic"/>

; Public Transport
* 5-minute walk south from {{ill|JR Sangu Line|ja|参宮線|12=draft|12=draft}} or {{ill|Kintetsu Yamada Line|ja|近鉄山田線|12=draft|12=draft}} Ise-shi Station.
* 5-minute walk from the Mie Kotsu "Ise-shi Station" bus stop.
* Immediate access from the Mie Kotsu "Geku-mae" bus stop.
; By Car
* About 5 minutes north from {{ill|Ise Nishi Interchange|ja|伊勢西インターチェンジ|12=draft|12=draft}} on the Ise Expressway.

